filesystems
-print working directory
-/ first slash represents root directory
-home is the name of a directory inside the root directory
-last part is username "willwags" for example 
-use cd to change directory ex: "cd downloads"
-cd.. to move out of a directory
- cd "" to get back in 
 -absolute paths
  -starts at the ROOT of the filesystem
  -/vehicles/cars/fords/mustang.txt
-cat to show the content of a contained file in a directory
-head and tail, show first or last lines of a file "head/tail -n 10 2023.csv"
-less and more,  more and less commands let you view the contents of a file, one page (or line) at a time.
-Re-run the less command, but this time, pipe cat -n into it so the CSV stays plain text while you browse with line numbers:
  cat -n 2023.csv | less
-touch command updates the access and modification timestamps of a file. By default, if the specified file does not exist, touch will create an empty file with the given filename
-If file.txt already exists:
  -The file contents stay the same.
  -The modified timestamp is updated to "right now."

  -If file.txt does not exist:
  -A new empty file is created.
-mkdir creates new directory inside or relative to current directory 
-move command moves a file or directory from one location to another/renaming
  -moving a file from the current directory, to the parent directory:
     mv some_file.txt ../some_file.txt
  -renaming
     mv some_file.txt some_other_name.txt
  -moving a file from the current directory to another nested directory:
     mv some_file.txt some_directory/some_file.txt
/ means and absolute path dont forget ..
-remove command deletes files or empty directory
-rm -r (directory name)
-cp copy command to copy from one location to another
-cp -R my_dir new_dir copies directory and all of its contents 
-ln symbolic links, creates links -s flag for symbolic links, creates another path that points to the original
-path to target comes first


